<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1902-11-07T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1902-11-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="25" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d25">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Bryan</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Petropolis</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-11-07"><hi rend="italic">November 7,
                                1902</hi></date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 466.]</seg></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Continuing the subject of my No. 464, of
                            October 31, I have the honor to report that the French minister informs
                            me that the legal adviser of the foreign office at Paris, in a lengthy
                            opinion, has sustained his position regarding the illegality of the
                            imposition of duties on merchandise in transit by the Amazon.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Charles Page
                            Bryan.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>